00:00:16.250 --> 00:00:17.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Hello and welcome.

00:00:17.810 --> 00:00:20.690 align:middle line:10%
Our topic today is the
mind-brain relationship.

00:00:20.690 --> 00:00:23.300 align:middle line:10%
And my guest is
Dr. Karl Pribram,

00:00:23.300 --> 00:00:25.760 align:middle line:10%
a professor of
psychology at Stanford

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:28.550 align:middle line:10%
University in the
Department of Psychology

00:00:28.550 --> 00:00:30.320 align:middle line:10%
and in the medical school.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.410 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Pribram is the author
of "Languages of the Brain"

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:37.890 align:middle line:84%
and hundreds of articles about
the mind-brain relationship.

00:00:37.890 --> 00:00:41.150 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I would say, fairly,
that Dr. Pribram is probably

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:45.860 align:middle line:84%
one of the most influential
scholars alive today in probing

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:48.650 align:middle line:84%
the mysteries of the
mind-brain relationship.

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:51.430 align:middle line:84%
Karl, welcome to
the "Mind's Eye".

00:00:51.430 --> 00:00:52.230 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you.

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:54.000 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a pleasure
to have you here.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.350 align:middle line:84%
You know, many academic
psychologists, and perhaps you

00:00:57.350 --> 00:01:00.050 align:middle line:84%
have some sympathy for
this point of view,

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:04.040 align:middle line:84%
over the years have taken
a perspective, which laymen

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:06.410 align:middle line:84%
tend to laugh at at
times, and they claim

00:01:06.410 --> 00:01:08.090 align:middle line:90%
that the mind doesn't exist.

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:10.700 align:middle line:84%
I wonder if you can
explain that perspective.

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:15.440 align:middle line:10%
Talk about what we mean, or
what you mean by the mind.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:19.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I don't like the term
the mind because it reifies.

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:23.720 align:middle line:84%
That means it makes a thing
of something that's a process.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:24.730 align:middle line:10%
We pay attention.

00:01:24.730 --> 00:01:25.910 align:middle line:10%
We see.

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:26.750 align:middle line:10%
We hear.

00:01:26.750 --> 00:01:28.730 align:middle line:10%
Those are all mental processes--

00:01:28.730 --> 00:01:29.530 align:middle line:10%
>> Activities.

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:33.505 align:middle line:10%
>> --mental activities.

00:01:33.505 --> 00:01:35.970 align:middle line:84%
But there isn't a
thing called the mind.

00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:39.000 align:middle line:84%
That might be something
you want to call yourself.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.470 align:middle line:84%
But the mind sort of makes
something concrete out

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:46.470 align:middle line:84%
of something that's
very multifaceted.

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:50.130 align:middle line:84%
>> And yet, somehow when I'm
aware of myself being aware,

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:53.470 align:middle line:84%
I think that, well, that's
my mind that does that.

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:55.175 align:middle line:90%
>> That does that.

00:01:55.175 --> 00:01:57.620 align:middle line:90%
That your mind does it.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:00.340 align:middle line:84%
I'd have to think
about that one.

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:01.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:05.390 align:middle line:84%
>> You are very well-known in
psychology and neuropsychology

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:09.699 align:middle line:84%
as the developer of the
holographic or holonomic model

00:02:09.699 --> 00:02:11.570 align:middle line:90%
of the brain.

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:13.190 align:middle line:84%
Can you talk about
that a little bit?

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:18.830 align:middle line:84%
And how it relates to the mind
or to the mind-body process?

00:02:18.830 --> 00:02:21.130 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:02:21.130 --> 00:02:22.880 align:middle line:84%
>> I have to be on my
toes with you today.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:23.720 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:30.590 align:middle line:84%
The holonomic brain theory
is based on some insights

00:02:30.590 --> 00:02:31.910 align:middle line:90%
that Dennis Gabor had.

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:33.590 align:middle line:84%
He is the inventor
of the hologram.

00:02:33.590 --> 00:02:38.280 align:middle line:84%
And he gained a Nobel Prize
for his many contributions.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:40.270 align:middle line:90%
He was a mathematician.

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:44.120 align:middle line:84%
And what he was trying
to do is develop a better

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:48.620 align:middle line:84%
way of making
electron micrographs,

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:51.290 align:middle line:84%
improve the resolution
of electron micrographs.

00:02:51.290 --> 00:02:54.110 align:middle line:84%
And so for electron
microscopy, he

00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:59.090 align:middle line:84%
suggested that instead of making
a photograph, essentially,

00:02:59.090 --> 00:03:01.340 align:middle line:84%
not with electron
microscopes, we

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:05.720 align:middle line:84%
make photographs by using
electrons instead of photons.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And he thought maybe
instead of making

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:12.050 align:middle line:84%
ordinary photographs,
what he would do

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:15.860 align:middle line:84%
is get the
interference patterns.

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:18.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, what is an
interference pattern?

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:22.100 align:middle line:84%
When light strikes, or when
electrons strike any object,

00:03:22.100 --> 00:03:23.380 align:middle line:90%
they scatter.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:27.510 align:middle line:84%
But the scatter is a
funny kind of scatter.

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:30.530 align:middle line:84%
It's a very
well-regulated scatter.

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:36.370 align:middle line:84%
For instance, if you
de-focus the lens on a camera

00:03:36.370 --> 00:03:40.930 align:middle line:84%
so that you don't get the image
falling on the image plane,

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:45.880 align:middle line:84%
and you have a blur, that blur
essentially is a hologram.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:47.600 align:middle line:90%
Because all you have to do is--

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:48.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Refocus is.

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:49.530 align:middle line:90%
>> --refocus it.

00:03:49.530 --> 00:03:51.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Contained in the blur
is the actual limit.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:52.780 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.310 align:middle line:90%
But you don't see it as such.

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:58.390 align:middle line:84%
And so one of the main
principles of holonomic brain

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:02.440 align:middle line:84%
theory, which gets us into
quantum mechanics also,

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:08.710 align:middle line:84%
is that there is a relationship
here between what we ordinarily

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:13.960 align:middle line:84%
experience and some other
process or some other order,

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:17.260 align:middle line:84%
which David Bohm calls the
implicate or enfolded order

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:20.290 align:middle line:84%
in which things are all
distributed or spread.

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:24.040 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, the
mathematical formulations

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:25.650 align:middle line:84%
are often called
spread functions.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.197 align:middle line:90%
Let's spread this out.

00:04:28.197 --> 00:04:30.280 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, what you're talking
about here is the deep

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:31.600 align:middle line:90%
structure of the universe--

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:32.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:35.990 align:middle line:84%
>> --in a way, beneath the
subatomic level virtually--

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:36.790 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:39.560 align:middle line:84%
>> --of matter itself are
these quantum wave functions--

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:40.360 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:41.160 align:middle line:90%
>> --so to speak.

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:43.102 align:middle line:84%
And they form
interference patterns.

00:04:43.102 --> 00:04:44.560 align:middle line:84%
Would I be wrong
in saying it would

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:46.630 align:middle line:84%
be like dropping
two stones in a pond

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.140 align:middle line:84%
with the way the
ripples overlap?

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:49.660 align:middle line:84%
And is that like
an interference?

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:51.850 align:middle line:84%
>> That's certainly the way
interference patterns remain,

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:52.650 align:middle line:90%
yes.

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:56.290 align:middle line:84%
>> And you're suggesting that at
that very deep level of reality

00:04:56.290 --> 00:04:59.320 align:middle line:84%
something is operating
in the brain itself?

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:01.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, no.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:03.010 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:07.000 align:middle line:84%
>> In a way, that's possible,
but that's not where

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.510 align:middle line:90%
the situation is at the moment.

00:05:08.510 --> 00:05:09.310 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:14.500 align:middle line:84%
>> All we know is that the
mathematical descriptions that

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:21.040 align:middle line:84%
we make of, let's say, single
cell processes and the branches

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:26.980 align:middle line:84%
from the single cells, and how
they interact with each other,

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:30.070 align:middle line:84%
not only anatomically,
but actually functional

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:31.420 align:middle line:90%
interactions.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:36.550 align:middle line:84%
That when we map those,
we get a description

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:40.912 align:middle line:84%
that is very similar to the
description of quantum events.

00:05:40.912 --> 00:05:43.120 align:middle line:84%
>> When you take into account
that there are billions

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:44.230 align:middle line:90%
of these single cells--

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:44.740 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:45.907 align:middle line:90%
>> --operating in the brain.

00:05:45.907 --> 00:05:47.750 align:middle line:84%
>> And the connections
between them.

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:48.625 align:middle line:90%
So they're even more.

00:05:48.625 --> 00:05:51.850 align:middle line:84%
They're trillions of
connections between them.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And they operate on
the basic principles

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.190 align:middle line:84%
that have been found to also
operate at quantum level.

00:05:57.190 --> 00:05:59.290 align:middle line:84%
Actually, it was the
other way around.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.960 align:middle line:84%
That the mathematics
that Gabor used,

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:06.010 align:middle line:84%
he borrowed from
Heisenberg and Hilbert,

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:09.550 align:middle line:84%
who developed them first in
mathematics, for Hilbert.

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:12.790 align:middle line:84%
And then Heisenberg used
it in quantum mechanics.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:15.190 align:middle line:84%
And then Gabor used
in the psychophysics.

00:06:15.190 --> 00:06:20.350 align:middle line:84%
And we've used that in modeling
how brain networks work.

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:22.720 align:middle line:84%
>> So in other
words, in the brain,

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:25.420 align:middle line:84%
when we look at the electrical
impulses traveling through

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:28.990 align:middle line:84%
the neurons and the patterns
as these billions of neurons

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:32.290 align:middle line:84%
interact, you would say that
that is analogous, I suppose,

00:06:32.290 --> 00:06:35.980 align:middle line:84%
or isomorphic to the processes
that are going on at the deeper

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:37.780 align:middle line:90%
quantum level?

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:40.990 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.020 align:middle line:84%
But we don't know that it's a
deeper quantum level, I mean,

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:44.900 align:middle line:90%
in the brain.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:45.910 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:48.200 align:middle line:84%
And that may or may
not be the case.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:51.150 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, analogous isn't
quite the right word.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:54.820 align:middle line:90%
They obey the same rules.

00:06:54.820 --> 00:06:56.270 align:middle line:90%
They obey the same rules.

00:06:56.270 --> 00:07:01.120 align:middle line:84%
It's not just an analogy
because the work that described

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:03.610 align:middle line:90%
these came independently of--

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:08.490 align:middle line:84%
see, an analogy would be that
you take the quantum ideas

00:07:08.490 --> 00:07:14.655 align:middle line:84%
and see how they fit to
the brain, the data we

00:07:14.655 --> 00:07:15.470 align:middle line:90%
have on the brain.

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:15.830 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, yes.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:17.480 align:middle line:84%
>> And that's not
the way it happened.

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:19.140 align:middle line:90%
We've got the brain data first.

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:19.940 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:26.480 align:middle line:84%
>> And then we see, look, it
fits the same mathematics.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:31.220 align:middle line:84%
And the people who are gathering
these data, including myself,

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:35.200 align:middle line:84%
weren't out to look for
an analogous process.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:37.340 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's a
very important point.

00:07:37.340 --> 00:07:39.477 align:middle line:84%
Because, otherwise,
you could be biased.

00:07:39.477 --> 00:07:41.060 align:middle line:84%
And there are lots
of different models

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:43.920 align:middle line:90%
that fit how the brain works.

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.550 align:middle line:84%
But this is more based
on how the brain was

00:07:46.550 --> 00:07:50.150 align:middle line:84%
found to work independent
of these conceptions.

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:51.720 align:middle line:90%
>> Independent of any model?

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:53.870 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, essentially,
independent of any model.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:55.870 align:middle line:84%
>> So you've got a
mathematical structure that--

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:56.670 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:07:56.670 --> 00:08:01.280 align:middle line:84%
>> --parallels the mathematical
structures of quantum physics.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, what does that tell
us about the the brind?

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:06.710 align:middle line:90%
>> The brind.

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:07.510 align:middle line:90%
>> The brind.

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:09.620 align:middle line:84%
>> That might be a good
Australian way to say it,

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:10.760 align:middle line:90%
the brind.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:18.020 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, what it tells me is
that the problems that have been

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:22.297 align:middle line:84%
faced in quantum mechanics
for, essentially, the century,

00:08:22.297 --> 00:08:23.630 align:middle line:90%
well, since the '20s, late '20s.

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:25.255 align:middle line:84%
>> Many paradoxes in
quantum mechanics.

00:08:25.255 --> 00:08:26.570 align:middle line:10%
>> And very many paradoxes.

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:30.650 align:middle line:10%
And those paradoxes also apply
at the psychophysical level

00:08:30.650 --> 00:08:33.409 align:middle line:10%
and at the neuronal level.

00:08:33.409 --> 00:08:37.490 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, we have to face
the same sets of problems.

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:40.220 align:middle line:84%
At the same time, I
think what David Bohm

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:43.970 align:middle line:84%
is doing is showing that some
of the classical conceptions,

00:08:43.970 --> 00:08:48.230 align:middle line:84%
which were thought not to
apply at the quantum level,

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.300 align:middle line:84%
really do apply at
the quantum level.

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:52.040 align:middle line:90%
Now, I'm interpreting Bohm.

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:53.870 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not
sure he would want

00:08:53.870 --> 00:08:55.750 align:middle line:84%
to agree to what my
interpretation of what

00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:56.550 align:middle line:90%
he's doing.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:59.720 align:middle line:84%
But to me, that seems
to be what is going on.

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:03.020 align:middle line:84%
So that the schism
between levels,

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:08.190 align:middle line:84%
between the quantum level,
the sub-microscopic almost,

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:09.450 align:middle line:90%
the subatomic level--

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:10.250 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:11.980 align:middle line:90%
>> --and what goes on there--

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:13.758 align:middle line:90%
>> --In the classical.

00:09:13.758 --> 00:09:15.800 align:middle line:84%
>> --and the classical,
the so-called uncertainty

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:19.200 align:middle line:84%
principles, and all of that,
that all applies all the way

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:20.000 align:middle line:90%
along.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.480 align:middle line:84%
But you've got to be very
careful in how and what--

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:27.590 align:middle line:90%
how should I put it?

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:29.930 align:middle line:84%
You've got to apply
it to the actual data

00:09:29.930 --> 00:09:32.990 align:middle line:84%
and not just sort
of run it over.

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:34.850 align:middle line:90%
>> Now, to the average layman--

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:36.275 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:09:36.275 --> 00:09:38.390 align:middle line:84%
>> --why would they
be interested in this?

00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:40.760 align:middle line:84%
Is there some significance,
say, to people

00:09:40.760 --> 00:09:43.850 align:middle line:84%
in their everyday lives,
or in their workaday world,

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.160 align:middle line:90%
in the business of life?

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:52.310 align:middle line:84%
>> Sure and this is the
critical thing that if, indeed,

00:09:52.310 --> 00:09:56.930 align:middle line:84%
we are right that these
quantum-like phenomena

00:09:56.930 --> 00:09:59.960 align:middle line:84%
or the rules of quantum
mechanics apply all the way

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:02.720 align:middle line:84%
through to our
psychological processes,

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.630 align:middle line:84%
what's going on in
the nervous system,

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:11.030 align:middle line:84%
then we have an
explanation, perhaps.

00:10:11.030 --> 00:10:14.900 align:middle line:84%
Certainly, we have a parallel
to the kind of experiences

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:18.080 align:middle line:84%
that people have called
spiritual experiences.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:22.880 align:middle line:84%
Because the description you get
of the spiritual experiences

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:25.335 align:middle line:84%
seem to parallel
the descriptions

00:10:25.335 --> 00:10:26.210 align:middle line:90%
that quantum physics.

00:10:26.210 --> 00:10:29.270 align:middle line:84%
That's why Fritjof Capra
wrote "Tao of Physics",

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:33.570 align:middle line:84%
why we have the woolly masters,
and all of this sort of thing

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:34.370 align:middle line:90%
that's come along.

00:10:34.370 --> 00:10:38.390 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, Bohr and Heisenberg
already, and Schrodinger.

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:40.590 align:middle line:84%
